  "prompt": "Why is every last name you see a male name?",
  "response": "The perception that many last names seem to be male can be attributed to historical and cultural practices. In many societies, surnames were originally derived from the names of male ancestors, reflecting a patriarchal tradition where men were often seen as the primary representatives of family lineage. Common practices include:\n\n1. **Patronymic Systems**: Many cultures have used patronymic naming systems, where a child's last name is derived from the father's first name. For example, names like \"Johnson\" originally meant \"son of John.\"\n\n2. **Inheritance and Lineage**: Historically, property and family names were often passed down through the male line. This reinforced the prominence of male-associated surnames.\n\n3. **Naming Conventions**: Western naming conventions often result in children taking their father's last name, perpetuating the use of male-associated surnames through generations.\n\nIt's important to note that there are many cultures and communities with matronymic systems or where surnames don't necessarily align with gender distinctions. Additionally, contemporary movements are increasingly challenging and changing these traditional practices, with more diverse approaches to naming in modern society.",
